<Document>
<name>Coronado Trail Scenic Byway</name>
<description><![CDATA[<h2>Coronado Trail Scenic Byway</h2><p><i>Arizona, USA · US-191, Clifton to Springerville</i></p><p><b>The lowest-traffic mountain road in the Southwest — 460+ curves from desert to spruce forest.</b></p><table style='font-family:sans-serif'><tr><td><b>Approx. length:</b></td><td>134 km (83 mi)</td></tr><tr><td><b>Drive time:</b></td><td>4–5 hrs</td></tr><tr><td><b>Best season:</b></td><td>April–October (snow above 2,400 m Nov–Apr)</td></tr><tr><td><b>Watch out for:</b></td><td>No services for 145 km between Morenci and Alpine; no cell signal; elk and black bear; snow at altitude</td></tr><tr><td><b>Track points:</b></td><td>340</td></tr></table><hr><p>This is the route Francisco Vásquez de Coronado followed in 1540, searching for the Seven Cities of Cibola. He found Zuñi pueblos and no gold. The modern road, completed in 1926, has more curves than any other US highway — 460 by some counts — and is famously the loneliest paved road in Arizona. You can drive 145 km and see fewer than a dozen vehicles. The route climbs from saguaro desert at Clifton to spruce-fir forest at 2,775 m at Blue Vista, dropping into the high pasture country of Alpine. Bring fuel and water.</p><h3>Scenic points marked on this route:</h3><ul><li><b>Morenci Mine overlook</b> — Largest open-pit copper mine in the United States; 4 km wide, 1 km deep. Terraces visible from the highway pullout.</li><li><b>Granville Recreation Area</b> — Picnic spot at the base of the climb; cliff dwellings and pictographs on nearby trails.</li><li><b>Rose Peak fire lookout</b> — 1934 Forest Service tower at 2,679 m — climbable when staffed in summer. Reportedly visibility of 240 km on clear days.</li><li><b>Blue Vista</b> — 2,775 m. The view drops 1,200 m into the Blue River drainage — wilderness country with the highest density of black bears in the Southwest.</li><li><b>Hannagan Meadow Lodge</b> — 1926 log lodge in a high meadow at 2,750 m. Mexican wolves were reintroduced to nearby wilderness in 1998 — howls heard at dusk.</li></ul><hr><p><i>Track geometry is interpolated between named waypoints — use a routing service to snap to actual road for navigation. Waypoints, scenic POIs, and notes are reliable.</i></p>]]></description>
